      "\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Convex.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Data.Real.Basic\n\n/-!\n# VCₙ dimension of convex sets in ℝⁿ⁺¹, ℝⁿ⁺²\n\nIn the literature it is known that every convex set in ℝ² has VC dimension at most 3,\nand there exists a convex set in ℝ³ with infinite VC dimension (even more strongly,\nwhich shatters an infinite set).\n\nThis file proves that every convex set in ℝⁿ has finite VCₙ dimension, constructs a convex set in\nℝⁿ⁺² with infinite VCₙ dimension (even more strongly, which n-shatters an infinite set),\nand conjectures that every convex set in ℝⁿ⁺¹ has finite VCₙ dimension.\n-/\n\n/-! ### What's known -/\n\n/-- Every convex set in ℝ² has VC dimension at most 3. -/\nlemma vc_lt_four_of_convex_r2 {C : Set (Fin 2 → ℝ)} (hC : Convex ℝ C)\n    {x : Fin 4 → Fin 2 → ℝ} {y : Set (Fin 4) → Fin 2 → ℝ}\n    (hxy : ∀ i s, x i + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s) : False := sorry\n\n/-- There exists a set of infinite VC dimension in ℝ³. -/\nlemma exists_convex_r3_vc_eq_infty :\n    ∃ (C : Set (Fin 3 → ℝ)) (hC : Convex ℝ C) (x : ℕ → Fin 3 → ℝ) (y : Set ℕ → Fin 3 → ℝ),\n      ∀ i s, x i + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s := sorry\n\n/-! ### What's new -/\n\n/-- There exists a set of infinite VCₙ dimension in ℝⁿ⁺². -/\nlemma exists_convex_rn_add_two_vc_n_eq_infty (n : ℕ) :\n    ∃ (C : Set (Fin (n + 2) → ℝ)) (hC : Convex ℝ C) (x : Fin n → ℕ → Fin (n + 2) → ℝ)\n      (y : Set (Fin n → ℕ) → Fin (n + 2) → ℝ),\n        ∀ i s, ∑ k, x k (i k) + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s := sorry\n\n/-! ### Conjectures -/\n\n/-- Every convex set in ℝ³ has VC₂ dimension at most 1.\n\nIn fact, this set n-shatters an infinite set. -/\nlemma vc2_lt_two_of_convex_r3 {C : Set (Fin 3 → ℝ)} (hC : Convex ℝ C)\n    {x y : Fin 2 → Fin 3 → ℝ} {z : Set (Fin 2 × Fin 2) → Fin 3 → ℝ}\n    (hxy : ∀ i j s, x i + y j + z s ∈ C ↔ (i, j) ∈ s) : False := sorry\n\n/-- Every convex set in ℝⁿ⁺¹ has VC₂ dimension at most 1. -/\nlemma exists_vcn_le_of_convex_rn_add_one (n : ℕ) :\n    ∃ d : ℕ, ∀ (C : Set (Fin (n + 1) → ℝ)) (hC : Convex ℝ C) (x : Fin n → ℕ → Fin (n + 1) → ℝ)\n      (y : Set (Fin n → ℕ) → Fin (n + 1) → ℝ) (hxy : ∀ i s, ∑ k, x k (i k) + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s),\n        False := sorry\n```\n\nThe goal is to complete the proof for `exists_vcn_le_of_convex_rn_add_one`.\nThe statement is: `∃ d : ℕ, ∀ (C : Set (Fin (n + 1) → ℝ)) (hC : Convex ℝ C) (x : Fin n → ℕ → Fin (n + 1) → ℝ) (y : Set (Fin n → ℕ) → Fin (n + 1) → ℝ) (hxy : ∀ i s, ∑ k, x k (i k) + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s), False`.\n\nTo prove this, we need to show that for any convex set C in ℝⁿ⁺¹ and any functions x, y satisfying the given condition, there is a contradiction. This would imply that no such convex set C can exist with the given properties, hence the statement is vacuously true with d being any natural number.\n\nLet's think about how to derive a contradiction from the given assumptions.\nThe condition `hxy : ∀ i s, ∑ k, x k (i k) + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s` is a strong condition. Let's analyze it.\n\nFor any subset s of Fin n → ℕ, the sum ∑ k, x k (i k) + y s must be in C if and only if i ∈ s.\n\nLet's consider specific cases:\n1. Let s = ∅. Then ∑ k, x k (i k) + y ∅ must be in C ↔ i ∈ ∅, which is false. So ∑ k, x k (i k) + y ∅ must not be in C.\n2. Let s = {i}. Then ∑ k, x k (i k) + y {i} must be in C ↔ i ∈ {i}, which is true. So ∑ k, x k (i k) + y {i} must be in C.\n3. Let s = Fin n → ℕ. Then ∑ k, x k (i k) + y (Fin n → ℕ) must be in C ↔ i ∈ Fin n → ℕ, which is true. So ∑ k, x k (i k) + y (Fin n → ℕ) must be in C.\n\nNow, let's think about the implications of these conditions.\nIf we take s₁ = ∅ and s₂ = Fin n → ℕ, we have:\n- ∑ k, x k (i k) + y ∅ ∉ C\n- ∑ k, x k (i k) + y (Fin n → ℕ) ∈ C\n\nThis means that adding y ∅ removes the point from C, while adding y (Fin n → ℕ) adds it back. This suggests some kind of cancellation or dependency between these terms.\n\nLet's think more carefully. For a fixed i, as s varies, the point ∑ k, x k (i k) + y s moves in and out of C. This seems to violate some property of convex sets.\n\nTo derive a contradiction, let's consid