      "by \n```\n\nSo, we need to prove that there exists a natural number d such that for all convex sets C in ℝⁿ⁺¹, and functions x and y satisfying the given condition, it leads to a contradiction.\n\nBut looking at the theorem statement, it's vacuously true because the hypothesis is contradictory. The hypothesis is that for all i and s, the sum of x k (i k) over k plus y s is in C if and only if i is in s. But this is a contradiction because of the nature of convex sets.\n\nWait, this is a contradiction because of the following reason: the hypothesis is that for all i and s, the sum of x k (i k) over k plus y s is in C if and only if i is in s. But this is contradictory because of the nature of convex sets.\n\nWait, but how is this contradictory? Let me think.\n\nSuppose we take s = ∅. Then the hypothesis says that the sum of x k (i k) over k plus y ∅ is in C if and only if i is in ∅. But i is in ∅ is false, so the sum must not be in C.\n\nBut then take s = {i}. Then the hypothesis says that the sum is in C if and only if i is in {i}, which is true. So the sum must be in C.\n\nBut the sum is the same in both cases, so it must be in C and not in C at the same time, which is a contradiction.\n\nWait, let's try to formalize this.\n\nLet's take s = ∅. Then for any i, the hypothesis hxy i ∅ says that ∑ k, x k (i k) + y ∅ ∈ C ↔ i ∈ ∅. But i ∈ ∅ is false, so the left side must be false. Therefore, ∑ k, x k (i k) + y ∅ ∉ C for any i.\n\nBut now take s = {i} for some i. Then hxy i {i} says that ∑ k, x k (i k) + y {i} ∈ C ↔ i ∈ {i}. But i ∈ {i} is true, so the left side must be true. Therefore, ∑ k, x k (i k) + y {i} ∈ C.\n\nBut the sum ∑ k, x k (i k) is the same in both cases (when s = ∅ and when s = {i}), so we have that ∑ k, x k (i k) + y ∅ ∉ C and ∑ k, x k (i k) + y {i} ∈ C. But the only difference is the term y s. So y {i} must be different from y ∅ in such a way that adding y {i} makes the element in C, while adding y ∅ does not.\n\nBut y {i} and y ∅ are elements of